<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>INTERNATIONAL&#174; VT 365 DIESEL ENGINE - FRONT COVER, VIBRATION DAMPER, and GEROTOR OIL PUMP - Removal -
        Vibration Damper
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="2">
        <title>Vibration Damper</title>
        <figure id="f2350501.5" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/d0731.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 216. Vibration damper runout</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Dial Indicator with Magnetic Base</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Paint removed, four points (90&#176; apart)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Before removing vibration damper, inspect vibration damper for runout as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Remove paint from face of vibration damper at four points 90&#176; apart.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Attach Dial Indicator with Magnetic Base to front of crankcase. Position indicator point
                    on unpainted surface.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Pry crankshaft forward and zero the dial indicator. This becomes the baseline.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Pry only in one direction to eliminate possible error induced by crankshaft end play.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Turn crankshaft 90&#176;. Pry crankshaft forward and record reading.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Repeat at each unpainted surface. If run out exceeds specification , install new
                    vibration damper.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To prevent personal injury or death, support the vibration damper during mounting bolt removal.
                    The damper can easily slide off the crankshaft.
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f2350502" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/d0701.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 217. Vibration damper mounting bolts</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Mounting bolt (4)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Vibration damper</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove four M12 x 59 bolts that secure vibration damper to crankshaft.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove vibration damper from crankshaft. Discard vibration damper retaining bolts. They are
                not reusable.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
